The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Godrej to hive off foods business

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, Jan. 3: Godrej Industries Ltd is planning to give up its foods business. The company will soon seek shareholders approval for the sale of the division to an associate company for not less than Rs 50 crore. 

 Godrej Industries, which has a diversified business comprising chemicals, medical diagnostics and foods, today informed the stock exchanges that shareholders would consider the proposal to authorise the companys board to sell, lease or otherwise dispose of the whole or a substantial part of the foods divisions. The shareholders will give their nod by way of a postal ballot. 

 Godrejs foods division makes edible oils, vanaspati, bakery fats, fruit drink and nectar. Some of the products include the Jumpin range of fruit drinks, the Xs range of fruit nectar, Tomato Puree, fruit pulps and juices in bulk packaging, refined edible oils and processed hydrogenated fats. 

 The foods division has two manufacturing units at Wadala in Mumbai and at Mandideep in Bhopal.

 The move follows the Godrejs renewed focus on the chemicals business that manufactures oleochemicals like fatty acids, glycerine, alcohol and surfactants such as alpha olefin sulphonate, which are used by detergents, cosmetics, pharmaceuticals and plastics manufacturers.

 The medical diagnostics division of the company was established in 1992. It is in the business of distributing diagnostic equipment and consumables to the medical sector. This division has tie-ups with Becton Dickinson of USA, the Nichols Institute of Diagnostics and Snijders Analyser in Holland.




